3. ‘Failing’ to Achieve Autonomy in English for Medical Purposes -- t14. Crucial but Neglected: English as a Foreign Language Teachers’ Perspectives on Learner Motivation -- t15. A Dynamic Account of Autonomy, Agency and Identity in (T)EFL Learning -- t16. Identity, Motivation and Autonomy: Stretching our Boundaries -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this volume researchers from Asia, Europe, the Middle East and North and South America employ a variety of theoretical perspectives and methodological approaches in their exploration of the links between identity, motivation, and autonomy in language learning. On a conceptual level the authors explore issues related to agency, metacognition, imagination, beliefs, and self. The book also addresses practice in classroom, self-access, and distance education contexts, considering topics such as teachers’ views on motivation, plurilingual learning, sustaining motivation in distance education, pop culture and gaming, study abroad, and the role of agency and identity in the motivation of pre-service teachers. The book concludes with a discussion of how an approach which sees identity, motivation, and autonomy as interrelated constructs has the potential to inform theory, practice and future research directions in the field of language teaching and learning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aSecond language acquisition. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  aagency in language learning.  aautonomy and language learning.  aautonomy.  aforeign language learning.  aidentity and language learning.  aidentity.  alanguage teaching and learning.  amotivation and language lea